dapted, to accommodate or respond to non-Greek understandings of reputation in society and culture. This collection of essays illustrates the ways in which the characteristics of fame and infamy in the Hellenistic era distinguished themselves and how they were represented in diverse and unique ways throughout the Mediterranean. The means of recording fame and infamy included public art, literature, sculpture, coinage, and inscribed monuments. The ruling elite carefully employed these means throughout the different Hellenistic kingdoms, and these essays demonstrate how they operated in the creation of social, political, and cultural values. The authors examine the cultural means whereby fame and infamy entered social consciousness, and explore the nature and effect of this important and enduring sociological phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFamexHistory. 0aHellenism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlexander the Great.  aCleopatra.  aHellenistic.  acelebrity.  aclassics.  acoinage.  afame.  afamous.  ahistoriography.  ahistory of celebrity.  ainfamy.  anumismatics.  apropaganda.  arenown.  asculpture.  asocial poetics.  awomen rulers.1 aAger, Sheila L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbantani, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Callataÿ, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Agostini, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaber, Riemer A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaber, Riemer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer-Bovet, Christelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Ju